The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, May 10, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, May 9: Tata Power Company has appointed international consultant McKinsey amp; Co to suggest cost-cutting measures across the organisation without affecting the quality of service, a senior Tata Power official said here. The ultimate objective for implementing the cost-cutting measures is to reduce the tariff from the present Rs 3.50 per unit to Rs 2.50 per unit. 																								 Mumbai, May 9: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) will focus on improving quality of intermediation and issues (offerings) in 2004-05 even as it has asked the National Stock Exchange to tone up its systems to avoid disruption in trading activity.																								 Mumbai, May 9: Industrial Development Bank of India (IDBI) will raise about Rs 1,000 crore through instruments like fixed deposits from the market till September 30, 2004. The plans for 2004-05 would be worked out later as the year 2003-04 has been extended by six months till September-end, IDBI sources said.																								 Mumbai, May 9: Videsh Sanchar Nigam Ltd (VSNL) has opened offices in the US, the UK and Hong Kong, and set up a new division  international business group  to handle the operations. The company has also roped in Asia Netcom senior vice- president Vinod Kumar as head of international business group, which will be headquartered in Singapore, VSNL officials said here today.																								 New Delhi, May 9: Software exports from Software Technology Parks of India (STPI) is estimated to touch about Rs 46,500 crore in 2003-04 from Rs 37,176 crore in 2002-03, registering a growth of 25 per cent, official sources said.
